================================================================================
Bundled dictionary content — glossary term definitions (redistributed)
================================================================================

JargonSlayer's built-in dictionary includes English and Chinese term
definitions ("glosses") compiled from the third-party glossaries below. Unlike
the transcription/model components above, this text IS bundled inside the app
(as data in @jargonslayer/core, generated from scripts/dictpacks/). Each
source's license below is a content/attribution license governing that glossary
text only; it does not affect JargonSlayer's own AGPL-3.0-only code license.
Per-term provenance (source + license for every entry) is recorded in
scripts/dictpacks/out/*.provenance.json. These glosses are MODIFICATIONS
of the source text: definitions are excerpted (typically the first
sentence) and may be truncated or lightly edited for length; some Chinese
glosses are hand-authored rather than drawn from the sources above (each
entry's provenance marks which).

--- Statistics glossary (dictionary pack "stats") ---
Source: Wikipedia — "Glossary of probability and statistics"
  https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glossary_of_probability_and_statistics
  Chinese glosses: leads of the corresponding zh.wikipedia.org articles.
License: CC BY-SA 4.0 — https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/
  These glosses remain licensed CC BY-SA 4.0 (share-alike).

--- Bioinformatics glossary (dictionary pack "bioinformatics-edam") ---
Source: EDAM Ontology — https://edamontology.org
  Ison, J. et al. "EDAM: an ontology of bioinformatics operations, types of
  data, topics, and formats." Bioinformatics 29(10), 2013.
License: CC BY-SA 4.0 — https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/
  These glosses remain licensed CC BY-SA 4.0 (share-alike).

--- Machine-learning glossary (dictionary pack "ml-stats") ---
Source: Google — "Machine Learning Glossary"
  https://developers.google.com/machine-learning/glossary
License: CC BY 4.0 — https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/
  (Code samples on that page are Apache 2.0 and are NOT used here.)

Chinese glosses not drawn from the sources above are hand-authored for this
